-- South African Equities Advance For a Fifth Day, Led By Old Mutual, Sasol
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-07-26T15:47:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-26/south-african-stocks-advance-led-higher-by-anglogold-harmony-and-datatec.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for a fifth day, advancing 74.83, or 0.3
percent, to 28,499 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg, the
highest since May 3.  
 The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  
 Datatec Ltd.  (DTC SJ) increased 85 cents, or 2.4 percent,
to 36.35 rand, extending a 3.2 percent advance on July 23. The
South African computer-services company was rated “overweight”
in new coverage by Morgan Stanley, which cited Johannesburg-
based Datatec’s potential to expand in emerging markets.  
 Gold Reef Resorts Ltd.  (GDF SJ) fell 70 cents, or 4
percent, to 16.69 rand, the biggest decline in two months. The
hotel and gaming company said earnings per share for the six
months through June may slide as much as 25 percent from a year
earlier.  
 Old Mutual Plc  (OML SJ), the biggest insurer in Africa,
rose 25 cents, or 1.8 percent, to 13.85 rand, the highest since
April 14. HSBC Holdings Plc and Standard Chartered Plc are in
talks to buy Old Mutual’s 52 percent stake in  Nedbank Group Ltd. 
(NED SJ), the Financial Times reported in  Mark Kleinman ’s “In
the Loop” column.  
 Nedbank, South Africa’s fourth-biggest bank, advanced 1.65
rand, or 1.2 percent, to 138.91 rand.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, climbed 2.49 rand, or 0.9 percent, to 294.49
rand. Oil traded around $79 a barrel in New York as sales of new
U.S. homes rose more than forecast and Tropical Storm Bonnie
dissipated without damaging production
platforms and refineries.  
